The spectrum between linearity/randomness implemented as a 'relevance spectrum' and an 'uncertainty space' have an alignment (the more irrelevant a connection, the more random it is likely to be) to some incomplete degree (since a random connection might be relevant in an unidentified way). Identifying the interface structures of this space and these related spectrums/variables is useful.
Applying 'relevance spectrums' is one way to navigate the 'uncertainty space' (these relevance spectrums exist between functions in the space).
Similarly, the 'uncertainty space' contains useful/relevant connections that can differentiate relevance types/positions/structures.
Another way to navigate this space is to identify other similar spectrums like the spectrum of in/dependence and complexity and generality that is present in this space, and identify useful connections across those spectrums such as indirect trivial connections or intersections.
This is bc most useful interface queries will involve different types of variation across different spectrums (as opposed to the 'same type of variation across different spectrums'), so identifying useful interface queries as 'combinations of different types of variation across different uncertainty-space spectrums' is useful.
As independence increases, randomness will also increase in most cases (except the interface network, which connects independent variables in an organized structure). A query that connects different independence/randomness/generality/etc types/levels/structures is likelier to be higher variation and more useful, but intra-level queries can also be useful, like connecting the 'first variants that indicate a clear difference (like a unit difference)' or the 'variants that when combined/iterated create an intersection with another useful structure'

div.div:
The usefulness of an index of 'usage/query/implementation/state variables of interface queries'
Normally the iteration of all possible solutions would be required, but bc these similarities to requirements were pre-computed, the query can be switched to using the pre-computed structure, so regularly analyzing whether a 'similarity to requirements/lack of pre-computed structures or pre-computed structures themselves' has been identified is useful.
The "probable distance to the solution" is useful to identify bc the "exact distance to the solution" is less likely to be identifiable during an iteration (except in cases like at the next to last step).
For example, after iterating some subset with some metric like a set of n% volatility functions, the remaining n% volatility functions might be skippable if they don't vary in other ways that haven't been identified as possibly useful yet.
Building an index of 'volatility/similarity/specificity/interactive/etc functions' is similar to building an index of 'usage/query/implementation/state variables of interface queries' in that function/query implementations can be usefully switched with these similarities.

div.div:
Relevance of structures like intersections/limits/embeddings
in general vs. specific networks
In the graph of 2-dimensional specific interface structures like volatility/validity that indicate relevance to a specific base like 'compared to other adjacent changes' or 'compared to a validity/truth network', you'll find simpler interactions than the 2-dimensionalization of general interface variables indicating relevance to a general base like reality, which are less mappable to each other given their independence, but which still have overlaps and can be clustered by adjacency, such as how differences are connectible to variation.
The 'standardization of each variable to a simple comparison to an adjacent base variable' is useful similar to how the 'standardization of these base variables to one base variable' is useful.
The intersections of interface structures like limits of these variables are so useful to identify that they may be countable to identify other high variation variable values like the 'usefulness/relevance value of the variable value set', like the relevance of 'high complexity, low abstraction structures'.
